to test certificate authenticity
openssl x509 -in cert.pem -text -noout
- openssl: Calls the main OpenSSL cryptographic toolkit.
- x509: Tells OpenSSL that you are working with the X.509 standard.
    X.509 is the universal format standard used for digital certificates (like the HTTPS certificates that secure websites).
-in cert.pem: Specifies the input file you want to look at. In this case, the certificate file is named cert.pem.
-text: This is the magic flag. It tells OpenSSL to translate the scrambled cryptographic data into a highly detailed, human-readable text format.
-noout: Stands for "No Output". By default, OpenSSL will dump the original, messy scrambled certificate text at the bottom of your screen after decoding it. Adding -noout tells it: "Only show me the decoded text, don't spit the raw encoded certificate back at me."
